      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Employment's New Age'' (editorial, July 30):</p>
        <p>It seems unlikely that corporate gatekeepers will soon shed biases against older workers that fly in the face of the emerging workplace realities. Three developments signal major change: a more durable and rapidly maturing population; the extension of work life to correspond with greater longevity; and a dramatically slower rate of growth in the work force as fewer new workers enter the labor market, even as demands for highly skilled workers grow.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Employment's New Age'' (editorial, July 30):</p>
        <p>It seems unlikely that corporate gatekeepers will soon shed biases against older workers that fly in the face of the emerging workplace realities. Three developments signal major change: a more durable and rapidly maturing population; the extension of work life to correspond with greater longevity; and a dramatically slower rate of growth in the work force as fewer new workers enter the labor market, even as demands for highly skilled workers grow.</p>
        <p>I hope that your editorial will awaken corporate employers to the enormous productive potential of a maturing society whose durability  is the richest legacy of the 20th century.</p>
        <p>CARL ATKINSON  Richmond, Calif., Aug. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
